Error\":false,\"timestamp\":1778083798777}}\n{\"type\":\"message\",\"id\":\"f7059ed0\",\"parentId\":\"9c2cc7dd\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-05-06T16:10:25.410Z\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"**Analyzing dynamic loading patterns**\\n\\nThe user mentioned using a dynamic loading pattern for classes or JARs only after the image is built, which I find interesting! It makes sense to avoid ordinary reflection in this context. Since the class exists at build time, it seems there wouldn’t be a catch. I'm thinking an alternative might be a direct public API, though using a custom loader seems impossible. That makes me ponder about the call site loader branch being inherently a custom loader.\\n\\n**Considering classpath loading**\\n\\nI’m thinking about forcing parent loading by not including the actual classpath. The method createClasspath seems to make userClasspath non-null but empty, and the AntClassLoader itself has no path. If I understand correctly, the parent fallback would load the same class, which seems like a good outcome. I wonder if getCommandline().getClasspath returns non-null even with an empty path; it likely does, but it's worth checking.\\n\\n**Addressing testing rules**\\n\\nI need to make changes to the existing test class since it's package-private and this violates the new rule stating all top-level test classes should be public. I should check the Checkstyle line length, which is likely around 120 characters, and ensure formatting is correct. I should also make static inner classes public. Additionally, I need to decide whether to remove Ant_junitTest.java since it poses a similar issue. Deleting it might be best, so I could use a bash command.\",\"thinkingSignature\":\"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_08dd4caa7ba0f2930169fb67d938a08197acf58e06cb267289\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-2fw3y0sCzgb6Oy6Wt2CUVNzoRKcsNR2Tl7PrSCrCpOrcjboOzpAFuzbXyc6Ti1DT48TFn740XTCTtHhr0CxXQtFnG